{
  "text": "Large-scale surveys, such as [CITATION_1] , are useful in identifying general patterns of older adults' technology use and informing models of technology acceptance about higher order factors. Other studies have revealed important information about older adults' usage and acceptance of specific technologies and perceptions about specific factors in models of technology acceptance. Many of these studies explored acceptance of assistive technologies (e.g., McGreadie & Tinker, 2005; [CITATION_2] , including smart home technologies (Demiris, Oliver, Dickey, Skubic, & Rantz, 2008) , and some focused on specific technologies such as video Uniform Commercial Codes (UCC) services [CITATION_3] , automatic teller machines (ATMs; [CITATION_4] ), E-commerce websites [CITATION_5] , E-government services [CITATION_6] , online shopping [CITATION_7] ) and personal digital assistants (PDAs; [CITATION_8] . However, less is known about the reasons that influence older adults' attitudes about the wide range of technologies available to them in their everyday lives. A thorough understanding of such attitudes can also contribute to the specification of models of technology acceptance which can increase their predictive ability.",
